>> The approach I took was to aggregate the errors in a single JSON object and return it, similar to what we do in some other RPCs.

> So this changes the way to detect wheter an error happened from looking at the JSON-RPC-level error to seeing if rv["error"] is a non-empty list?

@laanwj Only for those errors which occur after the rpc call has successfully created a new transaction, so that the user doesn't think the RPC failed when it actually succeeded.  (For errors that prevent the creation of a new transaction, a JSON-RPC exception is returned as before.)

